description.text:
This is a simple print to help level the bed.

Scale it to fit on your printers bed.
If the print is too 'squished', your bed is too low.
If the print is 'squiggly', your bed is too high.

Adjust as necessary.

Updated

v2 now is scaled at 100mm x 100mm x .1mm
Each line is 1mm thick.
Removed the center of the square to save time as its the corners that matter most.

When you're scaling this model to match your bed size, be sure to adjust the z scale to match your layer height. If its .4mm, then multiply by 400%. If its 0.175mm layer height, multiply by 175%.. etc...

If your bed dimensions are 150mm x 200mm, you'd scale the object by 150% and 200%.
If your bed dimensions are 200mm x 126mm, you'd scale the object by 200% and 126%.

Makes it very easy to scale for your bed size.

Used inkscape to create/dimension the shape.

  1. Draw a dimensioned square - Set stroke width to .2mm - no Fill
  2. Draw numerous horizontal lines (stroke to .2mm width) and use the Align/Distribute option to evenly space them across the square.
  3. Group and duplicate.
  4. Rotate each 45 then -45 degrees.
  5. Stroke to Path Everything
  6. Combine Everything
  7. Save to a Plain SVG.

Import the svg into blender.

  1. Be sure the sizing is correct ('N' menu)
  2. Convert to Mesh
  3. Edit and extrude to .2mm tall.
  4. Add cube, scale to fit outer square.
  5. Boolean modify (intersect) the grid w/ the cube.
  6. Do normal blender operations for mesh cleanup (limited dissolve, remove double vertexes, limited dissolve, set face normals outside, manual cleanup if necessary which it wasn't)
  7. Export STL.

EDIT 9/2/16: I've looked into both bed clips. Edits as follows:
The right clip had its horizontal arms extended by 1mm to better fit the black bed frame. This puts the total difference to 4mm, the same as the difference of the distance of the inner screw to the edge of the frame.
The left clip had the vertical catch on the top horizontal arm reduced by 2mm to match the distance on the right side. This was a mistake I overlooked when designing the part. Overall, it shouldn't affect functionality, but it should help with getting the arm between the bed and the bed frame.

Doesn't Matter

Yes

20%

Notes:

The bed clips should be the only parts that need support.

You will need 1 of each piece, except for "Edge Clip Top", print off 2 of these.

You will also need 2 M3 screws and corresponding nuts, as well as a 1/4 inch screw with a nut.

The bed clips snap onto the black frame of the bed, with the holes vertical on the top. this should place the hook on the bottom and leave the 2 L shaped arms on the side corresponding to the part names, one on the front and the other between the bed and the black frame.

The "Edge Clip Top will go on the arms on the top and will hook onto the bottom of the sheet metal frame, and the "Edge Clip left/right" will go on the arm on the front with the corresponding side (The left clip should be shorter than the right clip. this is because of the depth of the rail mounts under the frame).

Find the Triangular "Cross Beam Tripod Mount", and hold it with the sloped block on top. Drop the 1/4 inch screw through the large hole, and then use the nut to hold the screw in place.

Flip this piece over so the flat side of the triangular piece is upwards (the head of the screw should now be on the bottom) and feed the M3 screws through the 2 smaller holes. Line these screws up with the holes on the bed clips and feed the screws through. Screw on the M3 nuts tightly.

You can now attach any standard tripod screw accepting mount onto the bed of your Mini! Its great for filming smooth time lapses where the print head jumps around and not the part being printed!

NOTE: I used a 2 inch long 1/4 inch screw and a second nut to hold the tripod accessory for my GoPro firmly in place. You can do without the second nut and still get a firm mount if you position the screw at the right orientation for your mount. This might be easier to do by attaching the nut loosely, tightening your mount, and then tightening the nut on the screw to hold you mount at the correct angle

title: Flex Filament Direct Drive Extruder (Max Micron and other Prusa i3's )

description.text:
note- Updated ExtruderV4_1 uploaded Feb 9 2017- there are some minor changes that can improve the performance, but also note the tolerances in the filament path are MUCH tighter so make sure your printer is building very accurately

Seen a bunch of extruder mods for flex Filament, some probably better. But I wanted to design my own and make it a exact swap out for my stock one. Honestly it's almost the same basic design with just a few tweaks to get flex filament to feed better and not have a place to curl up or work out of the extruder. Also didn't want to have to get more screws and such.

• direct replacement for Max Micron (and most other Prusa i3 clones)
• No extra screws or springs needed, use the ones off the stock setup.
• better. more reliable feed into the extruder gear with a longer better directed tube in arm
• No place for flex filament to worm it's way out of the extruder like it does at times with stock unit.

notes - I highly recommend using concentric supports if you print with either part flat on their side. about 18% support coverage.
Use at least 3 nozzle widths for shell and at least 1mm top/bottom layering.
15%- 20% infill works fine as long as the outer shell is thick enough
Add the alternating shell with infill if you have it in your slicer.

if using ExtruderV4_1 please be aware that you can't pull hot filament out as the filament path is very tight with that piece. you need to back out the filament 3-5mm to release from the nozzle and then let cool before pulling though or hot plastic may stick to the extruders throat and block the next filament from being able to load!!

description.text:
Updated to include an xMinStop solution. Not super robust on the carriage side, but it should do.

Got this working with Marlin 1.1.0-RC7.

Updated 2/27/2017: Attached Marlin 1.1.0-RC7 configuration.h. There was a bug in this version that made the Z_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER not behave as expected so the included value is probably wrong.

This is what my probe offsets are:
X_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -23 // X offset: -left +right [of the nozzle]
Y_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER 0 // Y offset: -front +behind [the nozzle]
Z_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -1.2// Z offset: -below +above [the nozzle]

Follow the instructions for the E3D V6, Titan and BLTouch for the rest of the changes to the firmware.

Hardware I used:
2x - M3x6 screw
2x - M3 nuts
2x - M5 nut
2x - M5x15 screw (at least 15mm long, at most 18mm)

The Plant Feeder by Kefcom unfortunately didn't thread nicely with PET bottles in my country, so I thought I'd redesign it to accommodate any bottle.

Unlike Kefcom's design, I capitalise on the fact that FFF/FDM parts are porous, and allow water to quickly occupy the voids in the "infill" volume and slowly seep through the feeder surface, almost like osmosis.

Controlling the Flow
Controling the flow by which water can escape through the feeder is be done by:

  • Poking holes in the bottom surface of the feeder (exposing the infill). I use four 1mm holes (made with a sharp poker or nail).
  • Chopping off the pointy tip, creating a direct conduit from the base to the tip, essentially the through hole in Kefcom's design. I cut off 3mm.

I also wrap tape around the base of the feeder to create a tight seal preventing air from seeping through the gap (draining the bottle faster than the soil needs it).

description.text: This is a simple filament spool holder that is constructed from a couple basic parts from Josef PrÅ¯Å¡a's core Prusa Mendel GitHub repository: https://github.com/prusajr/PrusaMendel. It's made to hold a Ultimachine-style spool.

To assemble this spool holder, you'll need the following parts/hardware:
-Four printed bearing guides
-Four printed bar clamps
-Two 130mm lengths of m8 threaded rod
-Twelve m8 nuts
-Sixteen m8 washers
-Four 608zz bearings You just need to snap the four bar clamps over the existing top bars on your Prusa. Then thread the nuts, washers, and bearings (with guides) in the correct order onto the two 130mm threaded rods as you run them through the bar clamps. Each bar, when complete should have the following parts in this order: nut, washer, bearing w/ guides, washer, nut, washer, bar clamp, washer, nut... (~30mm gap) ...nut, washer, bar clamp, washer, nut, washer, baring w/ guides, washer, nut.

Summary

When soldering much, it is safer to use a suction device to avoid breathing in soldering foam. This one-thing-design let You mount a 120mm fan and a 135mm carbon filter with low budget.

I stacked two of them an connected them with a profile of metal using the bottom front holes. You can also use 20x40 or 20x60 mm aluminum profile with M3 slot nuts to get a solid stand space.

The device works good in a distance of 10cm behind the soldering work.

Important: pay attention to arrows on fan to mount it sucking the foam.

Materials

carbon filter

  • Xytronic Replacement Filter 135x135x9mm (their site says 130x130x10)
  • but from Reichelt i received 135x135x9mm
  • to get at: Reichelt , product: FILTER 426-3

fan

  • 120mm (105mm hole distance)
  • four fan mounting screws (also used in computers)
  • I used old ones lying around...

power supply

  • matching voltage
  • matching maximum current summed up for all parallel fans
  • computer fans 120mm: typical 12V / 0.3A
  • I used a wall wart with extra switch in 12V-line

Mounting Points

four holes front/bottom (M3, through):

  • mount the suction device on back side
  • I used the outer two holes and screwed in a M4x40 cylinder head bolt as stand, because my metal profile is only 15x15 mm and has got to less stand area

three holes inside/bottom (M3, countersunk):

  • mount on base

four holes front, center:

  • if filter won't hold itself, you could tap these holes (M3) to lock it sliding in "StegFilter"-Part

description.text:
This 2.5D Stegosaurus is a member of the three layered animal (tla) family. The upright plates on the back of the stegosaurus make it pretty memorable. Unfortunately the simplification lead to a loss of the tail spikes, which are quite interesting as well.

This build was done on a desktop cnc-machine by Stepcraft from 6.5 mm beech plywood using a spiral-toothed 1.2 mm flute. After machining it needed a little sanding and simple gluing together.

A laser cutter might be a good alternative tool to create (even) smaller versions.

Probably you could make a aluminum version and screw the parts together to get tiny key fob.

You can visit Visit https://www.zenziwerken.de/en/Spielsachen/Tiere for more animals.

I searched the web for reference pictures and traced the vectors using Illustrator. Then I build the model in SketchUp to take a look at the design before wasting material.

The circles can be used for alignment and/or as screw-holes. I inserted a wooden rod which helped a lot when gluing together.

After making the plastic ball joints to replace the originals on the FLSun i had to make an alignment jig.

Print 2 of the plates, secure them to the bench or a piece of wood and set the pins so they are exactly the same distance for pin 1 to pin pin 6. For the FLSun this is about 214mm

Put some glue on inside the socket on the plastic eyes then slip the carbon fiber rod inside, while the glue is wet put the arm in the jig so the eyes slip over the pins poking up and push them down snug.

Wait for the glue to try then remove.

I would suggest using something like a 2 pot epoxy so if you have to remove the eyes you can apply a little bit of heat and pull them off.

print_settings.Notes:: Filament: Hatchbox Black PLA

description.text:
I am a big fan of the game RuneScape and decided to design and print the Water Rune from the game. I also sanded and painted it to look more stone like and so I could cast them in resin and sell them on my Etsy Store.

I also did a Time Lapse of the print.

Printer:

Monoprice Maker Select

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.25mm

Infill:

15%

Notes:
  • Filament: Hatchbox Black PLA
  • Extruder Temp: 210C
  • Bed Temp: 60C

Sanding

I sanded with regular sandpaper you can buy anywhere starting a 80 grit and working my way up to 400 grit. It is important to sand against the layers of the 3d print so that that they start to blend better.

Painting

After sanding I painted it with two coats with Rust-Oleum Sandable 2in1 Primer Filler. You may have to do some sanding in between coats depending on what type of finish you want to achive.

*Optional* Silicon Mold

Since I wanted an easy and quick way of producing and selling these I opted out to make a mold out of Two Part Silicone. A channel called Punished Props has a great Tutorial Series which I followed to make my mold.

*Optional* Casting

After waiting about 8 hours for my mold to cure I poured a Two Part Resin in and let it cure for about 20 minutes and pulled it out. I recommend putting a small layer of something like baby powder (I used some corn starch I had laying around) into the mold before casting because it will make it easier to remove the cast piece from the mold and hide any left over layer lines or bubbles that are in the mold. The YouTube playlist I linked will explain better and more thoroughly than I can.

Detail Painting

If you decided to cast your part in resin you will need to repaint a gray base color. If you are just using your finished 3d print then this part is up to your imagination. What I did was paint the runestone with Rust-Oleum Gray Stone textured spray paint. I then got an Acrylic Paint Kit and painted the water symbol blue. I then decided to repaint the symbol with some sparkly fingernail polish since I wasn't satisfied with the look of the acrylic paint.

title: Prusa Z-Rod Constraint With Endstop Mount

description.text: The Prusa Z-Rod Constraint is a wonderful thing but its lacking a decent endstop mount. There is another derivative with an endstop mount on thingiverse but we found we broke it too easily or ruined endstops by accidentally getting glue in it.

Supportless Version I have added a supportless version (rev2) of the endstop mount that has elongated screw holes so you can make your adjustments at the endstop and not by moving the z constraint along the rod. The original enstop mount will need to be printed with support. You will need: 2 x M3-14 Screws (will need shorter with rev2)
2 x M3 Hex Nuts (the tiny ones about 5mm big)
2 x M3 Washers (Optional)
1 x M4-20 Screw
2x M4 Washers
1x M4 Nut
1 x endstop
1 x 608 skate bearing You will probably have to drill out the mounting holes on the endstop with a dremel to get the m3 screws thru the end stop.

title: Idler Pulley 20T 5mm Bore for Rostock / Reprap / Geeetech G2S Pro
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
One of my idler pulley bearing's gave up, so I had to fashion a fix from some screws, and it was not pretty.

However, I repaired it enough to enable me to make this model in Tinkercad and print so I have spares now.

It prints in two halves, and the hole in the middle is 5.5mm so the existing screw will just slide straight through.

To join the two halves, I placed them together with a nut and bolt, and then touched a soldering iron around the centre to seal them together. You could use Superglue etc..

Print on 0.2mm, no Brim, with a skirt (to wipe of excess) and 100% infill.

You don't need a bearing for this part, it will replace the whole idler pulley. (see photos)

NOTE: This is not a replacement part. Just something to get you up and running until you get the proper metal part from a supplier (in my case, two weeks from China!)

title: Combined width & horizontal size compensation calibration part
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A common problem with using the well-known calibration cube of arbitrary size to calibrate x/y scaling (e.g. stepper steps per mm for cartesian printers) is it omits any increase of width due to the FDM extrusion process (talking about those small ripples at the edge of your part).

Other calibration parts suggest to reduce your flow rate to adjust wall thickness, but this is a VERY bad idea, as this (lengthty) explanation shows: http://forums.reprap.org/read.php?1,704450

To exactly calibrate for A) x and y scaling and B) horizontal size compensation or exact wall thickness, this thing here should help you:

  • Print Part1.stl (the bigger part) and measure inner dimension (ID) and outer dimensions (OD) on both the x and y axis.

Then for both axes seperately:

  • Your new scaling factor (e.g. steps per mm) is: Old scaling factor * ( 100 mm / (ID + OD) )
  • Your walls are printed to thick by: (20 mm + ID - OD) / 2.

To reduce wall thickness use appropriate tools, such as the "horizontal size compensation" Simplify3D offers in the "Others" tab. The value to put there is (OD - ID -20 mm) / 4.

  • After putting in all compensations, print both Part1.stl and Part2. stl. They should fit each other quite nicely (you gotta push a bit, but not crazy). If they don't fit yet, further increase wall thickness compensation a bit.

Hope that helps, have fun!

description.text:
I broke my Extruder and needed this in a hurry.
Lost original files, so I designed this instead.

I can say this works, but I'm not happy with it and will Bowden up at some point.

Native files included for easy modifying. - Who needs the hassel of importing STL files?
Step are good, so where SAT, but STL are awful.

Drawn in Creo Direct Modelling (Personal Edition).

If anyone needs any design services, let me know. I am mercenary these days.
